LEGIONNAIRE'S DISEASE EPIDEMIOLOGY (6)
======================================
[Collecting further replies on differentiating community acquired
and nosocomial cases, continued from "Legionnaire's disease
epidemiology" (4) and (5):]

[1]
From: brnbaum@unixg.ubc.ca (David Birnbaum)
Received: Fri, 5 Jan 1996 18:54:00 -0500

As Dr. Wallis already suggested, the first step is to establish a diagnosis.
If it is confirmed as Legionella spp., then consider whether there is any
epidemiologic link between your two cases. From what you describe, there is
no suspicion of common source exposure (unless, of course, both cases
resided down-wind of some point source elsewhere in the community). Unless
person "A" was readmitted soon after a previous discharge, that case sounds
like a community acquired disease, and any of a number of infectious
diseases would be more common than Legionnaire's Disease. Person "B" could
be relapse or superinfection, from what you described; again, any of a
number of pathogens are likely. Person-to-person transmission would be most
unusual: if you have a cluster of cases, then typing to determine clonal
relationship between isolates could be useful (J CLIN MICROBIOL contains a
number of good references on typing Legionella spp.). Onset of disease
after the second day of hospitalization is a clue to infections being
nosocomial, but an incubation period long enough to extend back to community
exposure prior to admission can complicate classification.
It isn't clear why you've suggested Legionnaire's given the information
provided, nor how you're involved in these cases. You may want to go back
to the literature to gain perspective on the problem of legionellosis in
hospitals. Victor Yu has written several good papers on risk factors and
disease patterns in sporadic and epidemic Legionnaire's Disease. There are
a number of good outbreak reports, some of which give a comprehensive
picture (eg: Struelens MJ, Maes N, Rost F, et al., Genotypic and Phenotypic
Methods for the Investigation of a Nosocomial Legionella pneumophilia
Outbreak & Efficacy of Control Measures. J INFECT DIS 1992;166:22-30).
--
David Birnbaum, PhD, MPH
Clinical Assistant Professor
Dept. of Health Care & Epidemiology
University of British Columbia
e-mail: brnbaum@unixg.ubc.ca
