[2]
From: AlaskaRay@aol.com
Date: Wed, 3 Jan 1996 19:58:00 -0500
In response to Jospeh Wagner's question about differentiating community
acquired vs nosocomial Legionnaire's, I would think, the distinction would be
made based primarily on history. The majority of L pneumophila is type 1, so
typing would not help. Additionally, nosocomial infection is estimated to be
at least 14% of all hospital acquired pneumonias, so it is not uncommon.
In the cases presented, I assume that Legionnaire's was diagnosed post
mortum, because the final bacteriologic diagnosis is not actually mentioned
in the case reports. Neither patient was reported to be immunosuppressed.
Both patients had severe pulmonary infections on admission though the second
(20 y.o.) seemed to improve then suddenly crashed after 4 days. It would
help to know the bacteriological findings throughtout the couse of both
patient's hospitalizations (i.e. what did the sputum grow at different
times). Also knowing what antibiotics were used, and when, would be helpful.
I see no reason to presuppose anything but community acquired disease in the
1 year old. But the age makes me think of the possibility of cystic
fibrosis. Was this looked for and was the diagnosis of Legionnaire's
confirmed? If the sputum grew pseudomonas at any time, CF should be
considered. The second case is not as clear cut. This patient could have
had an initial rally due to good pulmonary toilet and better hydration, or he
could have acquired the Legionnaire's after being placed on the ventilator
(with an incubation period of as little as 2 days, this is certainly
possible).
I would also be interested to know if these patients had anything in common,
such at temporally related admissions, or use of the same ventilator or same
room.
I hope this helps, though I'm afraid it raises more questions than it
answers.
--
Ray Weinstein, MD Dale City, Va.
e-mail: AlaskaRay@aol.com
